  }), "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KPZWKrr-fmE"), "\ncomo arrumar um kytzynho\nBreaden snap"), mdx("p", null, "Livrinho pra guardar os micro anz\xF3is "), mdx("p", null, "Vara\nMost micro fishing is by sight so use a longer rod that will allow you to sneak up on the fish without scaring them. Several good options are crappie rods and heavier weight fly rods.  Both of these options may have disadvantages to be aware of and avoid. Crappie rods (panfish rods) will be your most dependable, available, and affordable option. Some of the lighter weight fly rods have very sensitive tips that will cause the bait to bounce around undesirably in front of the fish.  Although far from ideal, a conventional fishing rod and reel can be used by attaching micro fishing gear at the end of the line. Most micro fishing will require a 9-12 foot rod.  Longer rods are available and will be excellent options so long as the bait can still be held steady.  When using a fly or crappie pole you will tie the line to the furthest ring of the rod leaving between one and five feet of fixed line.  Japanese tenkara rods designed for tanago can be excellent micro fishing rods but the best models tend to be expensive and other are short and difficult to use unless on a dock or structure immediately adjacent the water."), mdx("p", null, "Anzol"), mdx("p", null, "The most important reason you should use small hooks for micro fishing is so you can successfully release micro fish back into the water with the least amount of damage. Barbless hooks lessen damage to the fish, however; this can be frustrating because of the difficulty in landing hooked fish. \xA0Some people use micro fishing for catching bait fish. This should not be done unless you are familiar with the fish you are catching and only keep the common species. Fly fishing tackle is a good place to look for small hooks and line. Find the smallest hook available. \xA0\xA0Anything below size 14 is a good. \xA0Ideally, the hook will be \xA0in the 20 and 30 range. \xA0Choosing \xA0pre tied, or snelled, hooks can save time and frustration. \xA0Also, look for hooks with a longer shank as these are easier to remove from the mouth of the fish. Japanese hooks, such as those used for catching tanago, a species of bitterling, are an ideal choice."), mdx("p", null, "Linha\nLine should be extremely light since most small fish have great eyesight and will not bite if they are spooked. \xA0Again, start by looking for line in the fly fishing tackle section. Find a high quality small diameter tippet. \xA0An alternative is ice fishing line. However, this is usually weaker and has a larger diameter for the same pound test. \xA0These small lines can be attached as a leader on to a spinning rod. \xA0A very small weight pinched at about three to five inches above the hook will help control bait and keep the line steady in wind.\xA0 Japanese equipment that is specialized for tanago can also be used, such as the bitterling kit listed below, and is best in murky conditions"), mdx("p", null, "B\xF3ia"), mdx("p", null, "Confeccionar usando madeira balsa"), mdx("p", null, "Outros"), mdx("p", null, "Worms work great for micro fishing. \xA0Many micro fish have very small mouths so the smallest piece of worm you can get on the hook is ideal. \xA0Using your finger nail, or clippers, will be your best options for preparing the bait. \xA0Maggots, blood worms, and gluten also work for micro fishing. \xA0When necessity dictates, a wide variety of other food sources can also work as bait for catching minnows. Some good baits you can purchase at the grocery store are bread, cheese, and imitation crab.\nThe depth of the bait in the water is important and will determine what species of fish you will catch. \xA0If the bait is teased on the surface of the water you will attract aggressive topminnows and other species that primarily feed at this level. \xA0Letting the bait fall to the bed of the pool or stream will entice benthic feeders such as darters and madtom. Time of day, swiftness of current, structures, and substrate are also factors to consider when targeting micro fish. \xA0Researching habitats and feeding traits of fish will increase your chances of landing the right species."), mdx("p", null, "Microfishing photo tank"), mdx("p", null, "Removedor de anzol usando uma agulha bem grande com a ponta de cima cordada pregada em uma b\xF3ia"), mdx("p", null, "Suporte pra linhas com anzol"), mdx("p", null, "livro identifica\xE7\xE3o peixes"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("h3", {
